tula</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a hole in the birth canal</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has severe physical and soc</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ial consequences and a devastating impact on women</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particularly</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> young </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">women and girls</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> who are at most at risk.</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The WHO estimates that more than two million </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">young </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">women </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">live </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> untreated obstetric</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fistula in </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Asia and sub-Saharan Africa</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">50,000 to 10</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">0,000 new cases each year.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Obstetric fistula is preventable and</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can largely be avoided by delaying t</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he first pregnancy, preventing female genital mutilation/c</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">utting </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensuring </span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">timely access to obstetric care. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:4pt 0pt"><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:4pt 0pt"><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Persons with disabilities have the same SR</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">H needs as other people. Yet they often face barriers to information and services. The ignorance and attitudes of society and individuals, including health-care providers</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, raise most of these barriers -</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> not the disabilities themselves. In fact, existing se</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">rvices usually can be adapted easily to accommodate persons with disabilities. Increasing awareness is the first and biggest step. Beyond that, much can be accomplished through resourcefulness and involving persons with disabilities in programme design and</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> monitoring.</span><span style="color:#4c4c4c; font-family:Arial; 